article.headline: Nebraska 74, Baylor 63
article.story: WACO, Texas (AP) -- Jake Muhleisen scored 20 points to lead Nebraska to a 74-63 win over Baylor on Saturday night. Marcus Neal added 15 points and Joe McCray had 14 for Nebraska (11-10, 4-6 Big 12). The Huskers led 42-38 with just over 12 minutes remaining after Baylor's Tommy Swanson went to the bench with his fourth personal foul. Nebraska's Jason Dourisseau left the game with 3:04 remaining in the first half with an injured ankle and did not return. The junior guard had three points. Aaron Bruce led Baylor (9-12, 1-9) with 16 points, but was tagged with his fourth foul with 14 minutes to go. Tim Bush contributed 16 points and Swanson added 14. "They had to play smart with the fouls," Nebraska head coach Barry Collier said. "We went inside, and our guys made a few more plays." Nebraska put together a 9-3 run and moved in front 51-41 with just under nine minutes remaining. "We got some stops on defense and pushed the ball up the floor," Muhleisen said. "We knocked down some easy shots in the fast break, and it was huge for us." Baylor closed the gap to seven points three times, the last one coming 55-48 with 6½ minutes remaining, but the Huskers hit 7-of-9 free throws in the final minute to clinch the win. "These were two teams in a must-win situation," Baylor coach Scott Drew said. "The second half defensively was the difference. That's the downfall of being limited in numbers."
